TY  - JOUR
AU  - Agarwal, Sumit
AU  - Amromin, Gene
AU  - Chomsisengphet, Souphala
AU  - Landvoigt, Tim
AU  - Piskorski, Tomasz
AU  - Seru, Amit
AU  - Yao, Vincent
T1  - Mortgage Refinancing, Consumer Spending, and Competition: Evidence from the Home Affordable Refinance Program
PY  - 2023
Y1  - 2023/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdac039
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 90
IS  - 2
SP  - 499
EP  - 537
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We examine the ability of the government to impact mortgage refinancing activity and spur consumption by focusing on the Home Affordable Refinance Program (HARP) that relaxed housing equity constraints by extending government credit guarantee on insufficiently collateralized refinanced mortgages. Difference-in-difference tests based on program eligibility criteria reveal a significant increase in refinancing activity by HARP. More than three million eligible borrowers with primarily fixed-rate mortgages refinanced under HARP, receiving an average reduction of 1.45$\%$ in interest rate ($3,000 in annual savings). Durable spending by borrowers increased significantly after refinancing. Regions more exposed to the program saw a relative increase in non-durable and durable consumer spending, a decline in foreclosure rates, and faster recovery in house prices. Competitive frictions in the refinancing market hampered the program’s impact: the take-up rate and annual savings among those who refinanced were reduced by 10–20$\%$, with amplified effects for the most indebted borrowers.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdac039
ER  - 



